Infinite Jest is a 1996 novel by American writer David Foster Wallace.
The novel is widely noted for its unconventional narrative structure (modeled after the Sierpinski gasket) and its experimental use of endnotes. It has been categorized as an encyclopedic novel and made Time magazine's list of the 100 best English-language novels published between 1923 and 2005.
Infinite Jest is a literary bestseller, having sold 44,000 copies by the end of its first year of publication. By 2016, its worldwide sales had exceeded one million copies.
